OPEN CV WITH PYTHON¶

NOTE: IN OPENCV RGB CHANNEL IS REPRESENTED AS BGR. FOR EG.,¶

RED (255,0,0)    -->   (0,0,255)
BLUE (0,0,255)   -->   (255,0,0)
GREEN(0,255,255) -->   (0,255,0)

READING AN IMAGE INTO A VARIABLE¶

MODES AVAILABLE:-
1.) IMREAD_GRAYSCALE 0
2.) IMREAD_COLOR 1
3.) IMREAD_UNCHANGED -1

img2 = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)    

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.xticks([])

LIVE STREAMING¶

In [7]:
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)

while True:
    ret, frame = cap.read()
    cv2.imshow('video-frame',frame)
    if cv2.waitKey(1) & 0xFF == ord('q'):
        break
        
cap.release()
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

GRAY LIVE STREAMING¶

In [8]:
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)

while True:
    ret, frame = cap.read()
    gray =  cv2.cvtColor(frame , cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)  # converting the frame to gray
    
    cv2.imshow('video-frame', frame)
    cv2.imshow('gray-frame', gray)
    
    if cv2.waitKey(1) & 0xFF == ord('q'):
        break
        
cap.release()
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

RECORDING A VIDEO¶

In [9]:
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)

ret , frame = cap.read()
y,x,channel = frame.shape   # getting the frame size

fourcc = cv2.VideoWriter_fourcc(*'XVID')
print(fourcc)

out = cv2.VideoWriter('jupyter-notebook-record.avi', fourcc , 20.0 , (x,y))  # output videorecording name

while(cap.isOpened()):
    ret, frame = cap.read()
    if ret==True:
        gray =  cv2.cvtColor(frame , cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)  # converting the frame to gray
        cv2.imshow('video-frame', frame)
        cv2.imshow('gray-frame', gray)
        
        out.write(frame)  # write to the file 
        
        if cv2.waitKey(1) & 0xFF == ord('q'):
            break
    else:
        break
        
        
# Release everything if the job is finished
cap.release()
out.release()
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

DRAWING ON IMAGES¶

LINE:¶

$cv2.line(image , start-point, end-point, color [, linewidth ])$

RECTANGLE:¶

$cv2.rectangle(image , start-corner, end-corner, color [, linewidth ])$

CIRCLE:¶

$cv2.circle(image , center-point, radius, color [, linewidth ])$

POLYGON:¶

$cv2.polylines(image , [pts-NParray], connectORnot, color [, linewidth ])$

In [10]:
img = cv2.imread('girl.jpg' , cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)

cv2.line(img , (0,0) , (150, 150) , (220,20,155), 10)

cv2.rectangle(img , (15,25) , (200, 150), (0,255,0), 5)

cv2.circle(img, (100, 63), 40, (0,0,255) , -1)

pts = np.array([[10,5],[20,30],[70,20],[50,10]])   # pts for the polygon
pts = pts.reshape((-1,1,2))   # opencv documentation recommends
cv2.polylines(img , [pts] , True , (0,255,255) , 3)    

cv2.imshow('image' , img)
img2 = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
plt.imshow(img2)
plt.xticks([]) , plt.yticks([])
plt.show()
cv2.waitKey(0)
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

WRITING TEXT ON IMAGE¶

$cv2.putText(image, text, startPoint, font, font-size, color, thickness, line-type )$

In [11]:
img = cv2.imread('baby2.jpg' , cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)

font = cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX
cv2.putText(img, '__Kaushal Kishore__' , (0,130) , font, 1.3, (0,255,255), 2, cv2.LINE_AA)

cv2.imshow('image' , img)

img2 = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
plt.imshow(img2)
plt.xticks([]) , plt.yticks([])
plt.show()

cv2.waitKey(0)
cv2.destroyAllWindows()
